00:01:03.110 --> 00:01:06.370
I'm delighted to welcome
you on behalf of Dr. Hayden,

00:01:06.370 --> 00:01:11.110
Librarian of Congress, to this
year's America's award ceremony.

00:01:11.110 --> 00:01:16.610
For 25 years, the consortium of
Latin American Studies programs,

00:01:16.610 --> 00:01:20.350
Tulane University's Stone Center
for Latin American Studies,

00:01:20.350 --> 00:01:22.550
and Vanderbilt University's
Center

00:01:22.550 --> 00:01:24.770
for Latin American
Studies have collaborated

00:01:24.770 --> 00:01:27.730
with the Hispanic division
here at the Library of Congress

00:01:27.730 --> 00:01:30.320
to celebrate children's
and young adult books

00:01:30.320 --> 00:01:33.540
that portray Latin
America, the Caribbean,

00:01:33.540 --> 00:01:36.330
and Latinos in the
United States.

00:01:36.330 --> 00:01:39.790
I'm aware that there are many
here that have been involved

00:01:39.790 --> 00:01:41.180
in coordinating this event,

00:01:41.180 --> 00:01:44.770
and I want to welcome
Denise Woltering-Vargas

00:01:44.770 --> 00:01:48.570
and her colleagues here
today to the Library.

00:01:48.570 --> 00:01:51.750
But I would also like
to take this opportunity

00:01:51.750 --> 00:01:56.030
to extend a very special
thanks to Georgette Dorn.

00:01:56.030 --> 00:02:03.590
Having worked at the Library
of Congress for 55 years

00:02:03.590 --> 00:02:06.790
and having served as the
chief of the Hispanic division

00:02:06.790 --> 00:02:10.360
with great distinction
since 1994,

00:02:10.360 --> 00:02:13.140
Georgette is retiring
next month.

00:02:14.250 --> 00:02:17.910
She began her career at the
Library of Congress in 1962,

00:02:17.910 --> 00:02:21.230
moving to the Hispanic
division in 1969.

00:02:21.230 --> 00:02:25.960
In her later role as chief,
she initiated the digitization

00:02:25.960 --> 00:02:28.130
of the Handbook of
Latin American Studies

00:02:28.130 --> 00:02:32.630
and the creation of the online
website and the digitization

00:02:32.630 --> 00:02:36.730
of the Archive Hispanic
Literature on tape.

00:02:36.730 --> 00:02:39.310
As well as making the
collections fairly available

00:02:39.310 --> 00:02:43.230
online, Georgette also
influenced those using

00:02:43.230 --> 00:02:47.290
or interested in
using these resources.

00:02:47.290 --> 00:02:50.180
Additionally, through
her administration

00:02:50.180 --> 00:02:53.120
of the Huntington
Society Gift Fund,

00:02:53.120 --> 00:02:56.720
Georgette has awarded
internships to hundreds

00:02:56.720 --> 00:02:59.220
of undergraduate and
graduate students to work

00:02:59.220 --> 00:03:01.760
in the Hispanic division.

00:03:01.760 --> 00:03:03.810
Many of those interns
are now members

00:03:03.810 --> 00:03:05.170
of the current generation

00:03:05.170 --> 00:03:10.300
of Latin American bibliographers
in the United States.

00:03:10.300 --> 00:03:13.330
Georgette's vision and her
passion for literature,

00:03:13.330 --> 00:03:17.900
scholarship, and programming
have left an indelible mark

00:03:17.900 --> 00:03:21.680
on our institution and have
strengthened the myriad roles

00:03:21.680 --> 00:03:24.750
that the role the Luca
[phonetic] Hispanic culture

00:03:24.750 --> 00:03:27.160
plays in the Library's
collections,

00:03:27.160 --> 00:03:30.140
outreach efforts
and programming.

00:03:30.140 --> 00:03:33.060
Indeed, the tradition of hosting
this particular event here

00:03:33.060 --> 00:03:35.990
at the Library materialized
in many ways,

00:03:35.990 --> 00:03:40.900
thanks to Georgette's belief in
the value of the Americas award.

00:03:40.900 --> 00:03:43.400
We wish her a wonderful
retirement, and we thank her

00:03:43.400 --> 00:03:47.570
for her countless contributions
throughout her career.

