00:09:31.900 --> 00:09:34.690
&gt;&gt; Julie Kline: Good afternoon.

00:09:35.960 --> 00:09:37.260
Wow, 25 years [inaudible].

00:09:37.260 --> 00:09:44.650
In his 1998 acceptance speech
for the circuit at the Library

00:09:44.650 --> 00:09:47.210
of Congress for the
Americas Award.

00:09:47.210 --> 00:09:50.960
Author Francisco
Jimenez said for most

00:09:50.960 --> 00:09:53.430
of my school days I didn't find

00:09:53.430 --> 00:09:55.450
in the literature
the experiences

00:09:55.450 --> 00:09:58.490
that I had gone through,
so I decided

00:09:58.490 --> 00:09:59.970
that it was very
important to promote

00:09:59.970 --> 00:10:04.620
in any way possible ethnic
American literature and also

00:10:04.620 --> 00:10:07.490
to contribute to that
body of literature.

00:10:07.490 --> 00:10:09.080
And I thought that it
was important to do

00:10:09.080 --> 00:10:13.270
that because the curriculum,
what we study in school,

00:10:13.270 --> 00:10:15.010
reflects who we are as a people.

00:10:15.010 --> 00:10:20.350
So if we do not see
ourselves as students,

00:10:20.350 --> 00:10:23.360
if we do not see ourselves
reflected in the curriculum,

00:10:23.360 --> 00:10:27.280
in the literature, in the
music, in the art that we study,

00:10:27.280 --> 00:10:29.550
then we do not arrive
at a good understanding

00:10:29.550 --> 00:10:33.740
of who we are personally
and who we are as a nation.

00:10:35.410 --> 00:10:38.670
From the start, our goals for
the Americas Award were simple.

00:10:38.670 --> 00:10:41.120
To highlight books that allow
children and young adults

00:10:41.120 --> 00:10:43.690
to see themselves
in the literature,

00:10:43.690 --> 00:10:47.230
to encourage U.S.
publication of such books,

00:10:47.230 --> 00:10:51.530
to showcase the diversity of
Latin America, the Caribbean,

00:10:51.530 --> 00:10:54.960
U.S. Latin Next, and other
diasporic Americas communities

00:10:54.960 --> 00:10:59.530
in the hemisphere, and
to encourage young people

00:10:59.530 --> 00:11:01.330
to read engaging
stories about lives

00:11:01.330 --> 00:11:05.520
and cultures perhaps
different to them.

00:11:05.520 --> 00:11:07.230
The Americas Award was inspired

00:11:07.230 --> 00:11:10.020
by the Children's
Africana Book Award, CABA,

00:11:10.020 --> 00:11:12.760
created by Africa Access
with the Outreach Council

00:11:12.760 --> 00:11:15.360
of the African Studies
Association.

00:11:15.360 --> 00:11:19.400
The book award concept seemed
a perfect project to propose

00:11:19.400 --> 00:11:21.590
to the class teaching
and outreach committee.

00:11:21.590 --> 00:11:25.820
I had some background that
made me really interested

00:11:25.820 --> 00:11:28.480
in internationalism
in children's books,

00:11:28.480 --> 00:11:32.010
and the committee at the
time was extremely receptive

00:11:32.010 --> 00:11:33.670
to the idea.

00:11:33.670 --> 00:11:36.390
And we did an event
through my center

00:11:36.390 --> 00:11:39.500
in 1991 called Reading
Latin America,

00:11:39.500 --> 00:11:42.290
both at Columbia Teachers
College and in Milwaukee,

00:11:42.290 --> 00:11:45.000
which was, I sort of count
that as a starting point

00:11:45.000 --> 00:11:48.710
because it gave us a sense of
what was out there at the time

00:11:48.710 --> 00:11:53.470
in terms of this kind of
content in children's books.

00:11:53.470 --> 00:11:57.270
The class committee helped
shape the award criteria,

00:11:57.270 --> 00:11:59.130
and in doing so,
we decided to focus

00:11:59.130 --> 00:12:02.080
on the multi-cultural
international dynamic,

00:12:02.080 --> 00:12:04.540
including the Latin Next
experience in the U.S.

00:12:04.540 --> 00:12:06.210
and including all the Americas,

00:12:06.210 --> 00:12:10.490
not just Spanish-speaking
countries and communities.

00:12:10.490 --> 00:12:13.220
We also determined the award
should be more than recognition

00:12:13.220 --> 00:12:16.280
of winners but rather should
include an annotated annual

00:12:16.280 --> 00:12:21.000
bibliography of commended titles
to be a guide for classroom use

00:12:21.000 --> 00:12:24.610
and for Library collection
development.

00:12:24.610 --> 00:12:28.860
As we refine the aware rationale
and criteria and discuss what

00:12:28.860 --> 00:12:32.220
to include and where
to draw lines, if any,

00:12:32.220 --> 00:12:34.560
I remember the comment
by Linda Hahn Miller,

00:12:34.560 --> 00:12:36.140
who was a former
outreach coordinator

00:12:36.140 --> 00:12:38.260
at the University of Florida.

00:12:38.260 --> 00:12:43.120
Said Linda, the world is made
up of lumpers and splitters.

00:12:43.120 --> 00:12:46.930
That is, people who think about
commonalities and connections

00:12:46.930 --> 00:12:50.430
and those who think about
difference in separation.

00:12:50.430 --> 00:12:53.820
I think for all of us shaping
the early Americas Award,

00:12:53.820 --> 00:12:56.700
we aim to be lumpers
through and through.

00:12:56.700 --> 00:13:01.750
So the award was further refined
over the years by the expertise,

00:13:01.750 --> 00:13:03.430
thoughtfulness, and commitment

00:13:03.430 --> 00:13:06.700
of the National Review
Committee members, all of you

00:13:06.700 --> 00:13:09.420
and all of your predecessors.

00:13:09.420 --> 00:13:12.250
And as it's matured, other
children's book awards,

00:13:12.250 --> 00:13:16.020
such as the Pura Belpre and the
Tomas Rivera were established.

00:13:16.020 --> 00:13:19.130
Each award makes a contribution,
and we've dovetailed with each,

00:13:19.130 --> 00:13:22.140
I think, in a way that
broadly benefits the field

00:13:22.140 --> 00:13:23.710
of children's literature.

00:13:23.710 --> 00:13:28.000
In the case of the Americas,
both the Award's recognition

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:31.170
of the diversity of
Americas and the inclusion

00:13:31.170 --> 00:13:34.040
of a criterion focused
specifically on potentials

00:13:34.040 --> 00:13:39.150
of classroom use helps make
it's contributions unique.

00:13:40.200 --> 00:13:45.470
So, I remember writing a letter
after the first competition

00:13:45.470 --> 00:13:46.820
when Becky Guenther, masqueraded

00:13:46.820 --> 00:13:48.120
by Lula de la Croix
[phonetic] run,

00:13:48.120 --> 00:13:53.210
I think we had a whole six
books on the commended list,

00:13:53.210 --> 00:13:54.740
and wrote a letter
to the committee,

00:13:54.740 --> 00:13:57.060
I believe there was onion
skin paper involved.

00:13:57.060 --> 00:14:02.620
It was back then, and it said
something about we'll look back

00:14:02.620 --> 00:14:04.950
on this 20 years from now
and look at what we started.

00:14:04.950 --> 00:14:07.390
Well, it's been 25 years.

00:14:07.390 --> 00:14:12.960
And there's been over 400 titles
recognized since 1993 as winner,

00:14:12.960 --> 00:14:15.880
honor, and commended books.

00:14:15.880 --> 00:14:19.830
And the ongoing relationship
with the Library

00:14:19.830 --> 00:14:22.650
of Congress has given
us a remarkable way

00:14:22.650 --> 00:14:27.270
to truly celebrate the books,
authors, and illustrators.

00:14:27.270 --> 00:14:32.860
Creatively coordinated since
2011 by Vanderbilt and Tulane,

00:14:32.860 --> 00:14:36.350
the Americas Award is stronger
and more vibrant than ever,

00:14:36.350 --> 00:14:39.720
and it's enhanced by the
innovative outreach programming,

00:14:39.720 --> 00:14:42.010
by colleagues at Latin
American study centers

00:14:42.010 --> 00:14:45.570
across the U.S. Diversity

00:14:45.570 --> 00:14:48.630
in children's literature
has a long way to go,

00:14:48.630 --> 00:14:51.370
but we can all appreciate the
Americas Award and in children's

00:14:51.370 --> 00:14:53.470
and young adult literature
has made a 25-year

00:14:53.470 --> 00:14:56.570
and counting contribution
to diversity.

00:14:56.570 --> 00:15:00.410
In recognition of books of
distinctive literary quality,

00:15:00.410 --> 00:15:04.290
cultural contextualization,
noteworthy integration of text,

00:15:04.290 --> 00:15:08.150
illustration, and design, and
potential for classroom use.

00:15:08.150 --> 00:15:10.510
[foreign language
spoken] Thank you.

00:15:10.510 --> 00:15:16.040
[ Applause ]

00:15:16.040 --> 00:15:19.590
I do want to go back
very briefly to,

00:15:19.590 --> 00:15:22.850
back to Georgette Dorn.

00:15:22.850 --> 00:15:27.800
The relationship of the Library

00:15:27.800 --> 00:15:32.910
of Congress has been really
valuable for the Americas Award,

00:15:32.910 --> 00:15:36.460
and it was you and I at
a meeting in New Orleans,

00:15:36.460 --> 00:15:39.390
getting in a car after
a committee meeting,

00:15:39.390 --> 00:15:44.090
going to lunch, and Georgette
said, we should have this

00:15:44.090 --> 00:15:45.390
at the Library of Congress.

00:15:45.390 --> 00:15:48.500
And I said, uh-huh,
that'd be really swell.

00:15:48.500 --> 00:15:52.270
It was because of Georgette
and the commitment of Georgette

00:15:52.270 --> 00:15:56.640
in the Hispanic division over
the years that we've been able

00:15:56.640 --> 00:16:00.650
to give this kind of
weight, this kind of value

00:16:00.650 --> 00:16:03.870
to the Americas Award, and
it's very much Georgette

00:16:03.870 --> 00:16:05.170
and the Hispanic division.

00:16:05.170 --> 00:16:06.970
So, thank you, Georgette,
very much.

00:16:06.970 --> 00:16:10.430
[ Applause ]

00:16:10.430 --> 00:16:13.680
I believe the Americas Award
has a present finally for you

00:16:13.680 --> 00:16:14.980
after all these years.

