00:16:36.350 --> 00:16:37.740
My little boy [inaudible].

00:16:37.740 --> 00:16:43.510
[laughter] Thank you all.

00:16:43.510 --> 00:16:49.670
[ Applause ]

00:16:49.670 --> 00:16:52.770
&gt;&gt; Connie Sharp: My
name is Connie Sharp,

00:16:52.770 --> 00:16:55.960
and I'm a district librarian
for Metro Public Schools

00:16:55.960 --> 00:16:58.230
in Nashville, Tennessee.

00:16:58.230 --> 00:17:00.850
I am honored to serve as
a review committee member,

00:17:00.850 --> 00:17:03.550
and I'm thrilled to
be with you today.

00:17:03.550 --> 00:17:08.290
I would like to recognize
the 2018 Americas Award

00:17:08.290 --> 00:17:10.450
commended titles.

00:17:10.450 --> 00:17:13.810
Several English-Spanish
bilingual picture books made our

00:17:13.810 --> 00:17:15.160
commended list.

00:17:15.160 --> 00:17:17.750
One such book is
The Little Doctor,

00:17:17.750 --> 00:17:19.720
written by Dr. Juan Guerra,

00:17:19.720 --> 00:17:23.120
and illustrated by
Victoria Castillo.

00:17:23.120 --> 00:17:27.520
In this story, a young boy
dreams of becoming a doctor.

00:17:27.520 --> 00:17:29.190
This delightful book is based

00:17:29.190 --> 00:17:31.570
on the writer's childhood
experience,

00:17:31.570 --> 00:17:35.640
and it is my pleasure to welcome
its author, Dr. Juan Guerra,

00:17:35.640 --> 00:17:39.090
his wife, Tammy, and their
sons Salvador and Sebastian,

00:17:39.090 --> 00:17:40.680
to our ceremony today.

00:17:40.680 --> 00:17:43.510
We are pleased to welcome you--

00:17:43.510 --> 00:17:50.090
[ Applause ]

00:17:50.090 --> 00:17:54.650
We are pleased to welcome you
and are inspired by your story.

00:17:54.650 --> 00:17:58.500
In Marti's Song for
Freedom by Emma Otheguy,

00:17:58.500 --> 00:18:02.980
illustrated by Beatriz
Vidal, we learn of Jose Marti

00:18:02.980 --> 00:18:04.970
and his tireless
efforts in speaking

00:18:04.970 --> 00:18:07.910
out for Cuba's independence
from Spain as well

00:18:07.910 --> 00:18:10.950
as the love he shared
for his two countries.

00:18:10.950 --> 00:18:14.310
Another biographical
piece is Ruben Dario,

00:18:14.310 --> 00:18:19.280
written by Georgina Laazaro
and illustrated by Lonnie Ruiz.

00:18:19.280 --> 00:18:22.860
In this poetic piece,
readers learn the story

00:18:22.860 --> 00:18:25.940
of Nicaraguan poet,
journalist, novelist,

00:18:25.940 --> 00:18:29.520
and diplomat, Ruben Dario.

00:18:29.520 --> 00:18:31.160
Little Skeleton's Countdown

00:18:31.160 --> 00:18:34.830
to Midnight charmingly
captures the celebratory spirit

00:18:34.830 --> 00:18:36.980
of día de los Muertos.

00:18:36.980 --> 00:18:40.780
Author Susie Jaramillo
engages readers of all ages

00:18:40.780 --> 00:18:46.170
in the countdown through rhyme
and enticing illustrations.

00:18:46.170 --> 00:18:47.890
Young People's Poet Laureate

00:18:47.890 --> 00:18:50.560
and former Americas
Award winning author,

00:18:50.560 --> 00:18:55.450
Margarita Engle captivates
us with her poetry in Bravo,

00:18:55.450 --> 00:18:57.950
poems about amazing Hispanics.

00:18:57.950 --> 00:18:59.590
The vibrant illustrations

00:18:59.590 --> 00:19:03.210
of Rafael Lopez complement
each diverse character

00:19:03.210 --> 00:19:05.930
and the role they
played in history.

00:19:05.930 --> 00:19:09.370
Margarita is recognized today
for having a second title

00:19:09.370 --> 00:19:13.020
on our commended
list, Forest World.

00:19:13.020 --> 00:19:16.070
In this timely novel written
in verse, she introduces us

00:19:16.070 --> 00:19:19.760
to the story of two siblings,
one in the United States,

00:19:19.760 --> 00:19:23.310
and one in Cuba, who
were unaware of the other

00:19:23.310 --> 00:19:28.350
until they are reunited to
spend a summer together in Cuba.

00:19:28.350 --> 00:19:30.740
Family stands as a
strong theme of several

00:19:30.740 --> 00:19:33.240
of our commended titles.

00:19:33.240 --> 00:19:37.060
In The Epic Fail of Arturo
Zamora, eighth grader,

00:19:37.060 --> 00:19:38.470
Arturo's summer gets off

00:19:38.470 --> 00:19:42.070
to a pretty typical start
until things go awry.

00:19:42.070 --> 00:19:44.760
Author Pablo Cartaya
tells an intriguing story

00:19:44.760 --> 00:19:47.250
that will have you rooting
for Arturo in his efforts

00:19:47.250 --> 00:19:49.580
to save not only
the family business

00:19:49.580 --> 00:19:53.060
but his community's
identity as well.

00:19:53.060 --> 00:19:56.250
Keeping with the theme of
family, The Inexplicable Logic

00:19:56.250 --> 00:20:01.600
of My Life, written by Benjamin
Alire Saenz, tells the story

00:20:01.600 --> 00:20:06.060
of a white 17-year-old boy
raised by a gay Mexican father.

00:20:06.060 --> 00:20:09.720
It is a story of resiliency,
what makes a family,

00:20:09.720 --> 00:20:12.530
and the connections
that bind us.

00:20:12.530 --> 00:20:16.110
In The First Rule of Punk,
author Celia Perez introduces us

00:20:16.110 --> 00:20:19.920
to Maria Luisa, better
known as Malu.

00:20:19.920 --> 00:20:23.770
After moving to Chicago from
California, Malu must deal

00:20:23.770 --> 00:20:26.620
with the familiar changes
of being a new kid in town

00:20:26.620 --> 00:20:29.910
and embracing her punk identity.

00:20:29.910 --> 00:20:33.850
We see a young girl become the
hero of her own story in Lucia,

00:20:33.850 --> 00:20:37.460
the Luchadora, by
Cynthia Leonor Garza,

00:20:37.460 --> 00:20:41.760
illustrated by Alyssa Bermudez.

00:20:41.760 --> 00:20:44.050
This delightful book
offers a cultural view

00:20:44.050 --> 00:20:47.190
of Mexican superheroes
and celebrates the courage

00:20:47.190 --> 00:20:51.390
and determination of
girls all over the world.

00:20:51.390 --> 00:20:54.790
Previous Americas Award
winning author, Monica Brown,

00:20:54.790 --> 00:20:58.450
brought us The Biography
of Frida Kahlo in her book,

00:20:58.450 --> 00:21:03.660
Frida Kahlo and her Animalitos,
illustrated by John Parra.

00:21:03.660 --> 00:21:05.820
This captivating
story is presented

00:21:05.820 --> 00:21:10.720
from the unique perspective
of her beloved pet.

00:21:10.720 --> 00:21:14.100
In the thriller Disappeared,
written by Francisco Stork,

00:21:14.100 --> 00:21:16.650
two Mexican teenagers
are inadvertently drawn

00:21:16.650 --> 00:21:19.570
into the world of drug
trafficking, kidnapping,

00:21:19.570 --> 00:21:21.110
corruption, and violence.

00:21:21.110 --> 00:21:25.580
Our last commended
title this year is Sing,

00:21:25.580 --> 00:21:28.770
Don't Cry, by Angela Dominguez.

00:21:28.770 --> 00:21:33.090
This story is inspired by the
Mexican ballad, Cielito Lindo,

00:21:33.090 --> 00:21:35.620
which is a loving tribute
to her grandfather,

00:21:35.620 --> 00:21:40.810
successful mariachi musician
Apolinar Navarrette Diaz.

00:21:40.810 --> 00:21:42.230
Please give a round of applause

00:21:42.230 --> 00:21:46.510
for the 2018 Americas
Award commended titles.

00:21:46.510 --> 00:21:56.060
[ Applause ]

00:21:56.060 --> 00:21:57.360
And now I have the pleasure

00:21:57.360 --> 00:22:02.840
of chairing the 2018 Americas
Award honorable mention titles.

00:22:02.840 --> 00:22:05.600
Our first book, All
the Way to Havana,

00:22:05.600 --> 00:22:10.230
written by Margarita Engle,
and illustrated by Mike Curato,

00:22:10.230 --> 00:22:12.410
is the delightful story
of a young boy travelling

00:22:12.410 --> 00:22:14.470
to the big city of Havana, Cuba,

00:22:14.470 --> 00:22:17.960
in his family's old
blue car, Cara Cara.

00:22:17.960 --> 00:22:20.300
Along the way they experience
the sights and sounds

00:22:20.300 --> 00:22:23.180
of the streets, the
beautiful cars putt-putting

00:22:23.180 --> 00:22:25.920
and bumpety-bumping
along the way.

00:22:25.920 --> 00:22:27.970
This engaging story
celebrates the spirit

00:22:27.970 --> 00:22:30.490
of the young boy's
family as well as that

00:22:30.490 --> 00:22:33.480
of the Cuban people they
greet along the way.

00:22:33.480 --> 00:22:37.230
Margarita Engle's masterful
use of onomatopoeia coupled

00:22:37.230 --> 00:22:38.530
with the brilliant illustrations

00:22:38.530 --> 00:22:41.270
of Mike Curato make this
an engaging read aloud

00:22:41.270 --> 00:22:42.570
for the young reader.

00:22:42.570 --> 00:22:46.520
Our second book,
Lucky Broken Girl,

00:22:46.520 --> 00:22:50.590
is based on the inspirational
story of author, Ruth Behar.

00:22:50.590 --> 00:22:54.260
Having recently emigrated
to New York in the 1960's,

00:22:54.260 --> 00:22:57.460
fifth grader, Ruthie Mizrahi
[phonetic], a Cuban Jewish girl,

00:22:57.460 --> 00:23:00.360
feels that she is finally
starting to fit in.

00:23:00.360 --> 00:23:02.770
School is going well,
and she has become known

00:23:02.770 --> 00:23:05.600
as the neighborhood
hot-scotch queen.

00:23:05.600 --> 00:23:08.910
Tragically, Ruthie is involved
in a horrific car accident

00:23:08.910 --> 00:23:11.080
that nearly cost her her life.

00:23:11.080 --> 00:23:14.470
She is so badly injured that
she is forced to lie in bed

00:23:14.470 --> 00:23:18.540
in a body cast immobilized
for nearly a year.

00:23:18.540 --> 00:23:21.420
This inspirational story allows
us to witness the struggles

00:23:21.420 --> 00:23:24.780
and successes that ultimately
form the diverse friendships

00:23:24.780 --> 00:23:29.720
that bring hope, healing, and
happiness back into her life.

00:23:29.720 --> 00:23:33.350
Please join me in congratulating
the 2018 honorable mention

00:23:33.350 --> 00:23:35.700
titles, their authors,
and illustrators.

00:23:35.700 --> 00:23:37.500
Thank you.

00:23:37.500 --> 00:23:58.300
[ Applause ]

00:23:58.300 --> 00:23:59.980
&gt;&gt; Emily Chavez: Good afternoon.

00:23:59.980 --> 00:24:04.860
I'm Emily Chavez, and I'm the
associate director in the Center

00:24:04.860 --> 00:24:07.120
for Multicultural Affairs
at Duke University,

00:24:07.120 --> 00:24:11.390
and I'm here also on behalf
of the UNC Duke Consortium

00:24:11.390 --> 00:24:13.500
in Latin America and
Caribbean Studies.

00:24:13.500 --> 00:24:18.680
It is my great pleasure to
present this 2018 Americas Award

00:24:18.680 --> 00:24:22.970
to Duncan Tonatiuh for
his children's book Danza!

00:24:22.970 --> 00:24:27.630
Amalia Hernández and El
Ballet Folklórico de México.

00:24:27.630 --> 00:24:30.710
You may know that Mr.
Tonatiuh is a prolific author

00:24:30.710 --> 00:24:33.520
and illustrator whose
work has been recognized

00:24:33.520 --> 00:24:36.450
by the Americas Award
several times.

00:24:36.450 --> 00:24:39.120
In addition to this
award we present today,

00:24:39.120 --> 00:24:43.310
Mr. Tonatiuh was a 2015
Americas Award winner

00:24:43.310 --> 00:24:45.200
for his book Separate
is Never Equal,

00:24:45.200 --> 00:24:49.940
and he won honorable
mentions in 2014 and 2016,

00:24:49.940 --> 00:24:51.630
in addition to having
multiple books

00:24:51.630 --> 00:24:53.710
on our commended titles list.

00:24:53.710 --> 00:24:55.590
Thus, I would like
to thank Mr. Tonatiuh

00:24:55.590 --> 00:24:57.040
for his many contributions

00:24:57.040 --> 00:24:59.510
to Latin American
children's literature.

00:24:59.510 --> 00:25:03.500
Danza documents an important
part of Latin American

00:25:03.500 --> 00:25:05.640
and performing arts history.

00:25:05.640 --> 00:25:09.300
It is the story of Amalia
Hernandez' life work

00:25:09.300 --> 00:25:13.020
to create a dance company that
brought to life the history

00:25:13.020 --> 00:25:16.000
and the many indigenous
identities and cultures

00:25:16.000 --> 00:25:19.050
of Mexico through
contemporary movement.

00:25:19.050 --> 00:25:24.210
Hernandez' dance choreography in
many ways was about recognizing

00:25:24.210 --> 00:25:26.940
and honoring Mexico's
history and in turn,

00:25:26.940 --> 00:25:30.200
Mr. Tonatiuh does the
same in telling the story

00:25:30.200 --> 00:25:34.120
of Amalia Hernandez' life
long devotion to her craft

00:25:34.120 --> 00:25:37.850
and the impact it made
on Mexico and the world.

00:25:37.850 --> 00:25:41.290
In his typical [inaudible]
inspired style

00:25:41.290 --> 00:25:43.920
with creative textures
and rich colors,

00:25:43.920 --> 00:25:47.320
Mr. Tonatiuh draws
readers into the pages.

00:25:47.320 --> 00:25:50.490
This book is the first of
it's kind to tell the story

00:25:50.490 --> 00:25:53.910
of Amalia Hernandez to
a children's audience,

00:25:53.910 --> 00:25:57.160
and in this way makes more
accessible a Latin American

00:25:57.160 --> 00:25:58.890
pioneer in the arts.

00:25:58.890 --> 00:26:00.890
I imagine young Latina dancers

00:26:00.890 --> 00:26:04.620
and any young dancer reading
this story with pleasure.

00:26:04.620 --> 00:26:06.370
Empowered with the knowledge

00:26:06.370 --> 00:26:09.420
of who came before
them, who paved the way.

00:26:09.420 --> 00:26:12.980
I would like to now
present Duncan Tonatiuh

00:26:12.980 --> 00:26:16.250
with the 2018 Americas
Award for children's

00:26:16.250 --> 00:26:18.510
and young adult literature.

00:26:18.510 --> 00:26:39.270
[ Applause ]

00:26:39.270 --> 00:26:41.900
&gt;&gt; Duncan Tonatiuh: Thank
you and I'm very happy,

00:26:41.900 --> 00:26:43.730
very grateful to be here.

00:26:43.730 --> 00:26:48.640
I want to congratulate my fellow
authors/illustrators whose work

00:26:48.640 --> 00:26:51.580
is also being celebrated,
recognized today.

00:26:51.580 --> 00:26:54.870
I'm very thankful to
CLAS to the committee

00:26:54.870 --> 00:26:57.900
for celebrating my work,
for choosing my work,

00:26:57.900 --> 00:27:00.600
and all these other
wonderful books

00:27:00.600 --> 00:27:03.300
that you're presenting today.

00:27:03.300 --> 00:27:08.280
I think, you know, the Americas
Award does a wonderful job

00:27:08.280 --> 00:27:12.630
in doing that and highlighting
and creating this list of books,

00:27:12.630 --> 00:27:15.380
this body of work that
celebrates Latin America

00:27:15.380 --> 00:27:22.050
and Latinos in the U.S.
I also really appreciate

00:27:22.050 --> 00:27:25.590
and feel very grateful to CLAS
for their continual support,

00:27:25.590 --> 00:27:29.590
that they've recognized
some of my work in the past,

00:27:29.590 --> 00:27:32.960
and in the job they
do, creating resources

00:27:32.960 --> 00:27:35.180
to use the books
in the classroom.

00:27:35.180 --> 00:27:37.430
I think that's something
very special and wonderful

00:27:37.430 --> 00:27:40.430
that the Americas Award does
creating different guides

00:27:40.430 --> 00:27:42.410
in different ways of not
only recognizing the books

00:27:42.410 --> 00:27:46.980
but to then making
them useful to teachers

00:27:46.980 --> 00:27:48.390
and to people in the classroom.

00:27:48.390 --> 00:27:52.220
I take the opportunity to
thank the people at Abrams,

00:27:52.220 --> 00:27:53.760
who made this book possible,

00:27:53.760 --> 00:27:57.100
and I feel very grateful
to the people there.

00:27:57.100 --> 00:28:01.490
And, you know, it takes a
whole team to create a book,

00:28:01.490 --> 00:28:05.030
and I've been making books with
Abrams now for almost ten years,

00:28:05.030 --> 00:28:09.130
and it's been a wonderful
relationship, and I'm very happy

00:28:09.130 --> 00:28:14.410
that they've supported my work
and helped it be successful,

00:28:14.410 --> 00:28:17.360
and I especially want to thank
my editor, Howard Reeves,

00:28:17.360 --> 00:28:21.120
who has always been
very thoughtful

00:28:21.120 --> 00:28:25.330
and has made my work
better by his thoughtful

00:28:25.330 --> 00:28:29.280
and careful editing but also
for being a friend and just kind

00:28:29.280 --> 00:28:33.210
of looking after me and
supporting my vision

00:28:33.210 --> 00:28:34.510
in the books that
I want to create.

00:28:34.510 --> 00:28:40.040
I want to thank my family, you
know, my wife, for her love

00:28:40.040 --> 00:28:42.700
and for her partnership,

00:28:42.700 --> 00:28:44.740
for being a partner
in this adventure.

00:28:44.740 --> 00:28:49.290
To my kids, who are just my, I
have a three-year-old daughter,

00:28:49.290 --> 00:28:51.540
[inaudible], and a
one-year-old son, Maximo,

00:28:51.540 --> 00:28:56.860
who just bring a lot
of joy and happiness,

00:28:56.860 --> 00:28:59.930
and I thank them for that.

00:28:59.930 --> 00:29:02.050
And I just want to tell
really briefly a little bit

00:29:02.050 --> 00:29:06.390
of how this book came about,
give you a little bit of sort

00:29:06.390 --> 00:29:09.770
of the story behind the book.

00:29:09.770 --> 00:29:12.450
My wife, Patty, she's a dancer.

00:29:12.450 --> 00:29:15.660
She's classically trained,
and she does modern

00:29:15.660 --> 00:29:17.680
and contemporary dance.

00:29:17.680 --> 00:29:20.600
And the last year she's been
aerial dance with the hoop

00:29:20.600 --> 00:29:24.900
and the straps and the trapeze.

00:29:24.900 --> 00:29:27.480
And I've done a few
illustrations inspired

00:29:27.480 --> 00:29:30.210
by her dancing, and I
like dancing myself and I

00:29:30.210 --> 00:29:33.610
like watching dance, so I've
made some images about that.

00:29:33.610 --> 00:29:38.340
And so it's something that I'm
interested in, that I like.

00:29:38.340 --> 00:29:40.550
My wife's mother was a dancer,

00:29:40.550 --> 00:29:43.820
and her grandmother was
actually a dancer too,

00:29:43.820 --> 00:29:46.330
and my wife's mother,
my mother-in-law,

00:29:46.330 --> 00:29:50.790
she danced with Ballet
[foreign language] in the '70's

00:29:50.790 --> 00:29:52.480
for a few years, and so that's--

00:29:52.480 --> 00:29:55.870
and it just kind of came up
in conversation at some point,

00:29:55.870 --> 00:29:58.820
and that gave me the
idea of making a book

00:29:58.820 --> 00:30:00.120
about Amalia Hernandez.

00:30:00.120 --> 00:30:04.270
So that's sort of on one hand.

00:30:04.270 --> 00:30:07.580
On the other hand, another
reason for doing the book,

00:30:07.580 --> 00:30:10.980
like I remember, I grew up
in Mexico, and I remember

00:30:10.980 --> 00:30:13.250
when I was like seven
or eight years old,

00:30:13.250 --> 00:30:14.880
dressing up like a charro

00:30:14.880 --> 00:30:18.530
and dancing the [foreign
language spoken],

00:30:18.530 --> 00:30:19.830
and it's a very common
experience,

00:30:19.830 --> 00:30:22.220
a very popular experience,
you know, for a kid,

00:30:22.220 --> 00:30:25.150
especially I think, you know,
to celebrate a special occasion

00:30:25.150 --> 00:30:29.570
like Mother's Day or the end
of the school year, to dance,

00:30:29.570 --> 00:30:33.100
to do, to perform
a folkloric dance.

00:30:33.100 --> 00:30:36.050
And later on when
I was a teenager,

00:30:36.050 --> 00:30:37.860
I came to the United States,

00:30:37.860 --> 00:30:41.690
and I saw in the United States
folkloric dance was also very

00:30:41.690 --> 00:30:45.380
popular and important,
especially for occasions

00:30:45.380 --> 00:30:48.120
when different kinds of people
celebrate their culture,

00:30:48.120 --> 00:30:49.880
celebrate their heritage.

00:30:49.880 --> 00:30:52.660
In the case of Mexican
American people, you know,

00:30:52.660 --> 00:30:55.760
on days like Cinco de Mayo

00:30:55.760 --> 00:30:58.530
or [foreign language
spoken] it's a way to show

00:30:58.530 --> 00:31:03.200
that you're proud of your
roots, to display your culture,

00:31:03.200 --> 00:31:10.680
and so I wanted to
do a book about dance

00:31:10.680 --> 00:31:12.820
and especially folkloric
dance, because I know that it's

00:31:12.820 --> 00:31:17.800
such an important experience,
not only in the country

00:31:17.800 --> 00:31:19.870
where it comes from,
in this case in Mexico,

00:31:19.870 --> 00:31:23.070
but also in the U.S., you know.

00:31:23.070 --> 00:31:25.330
And when I heard my
mother-in-law talking

00:31:25.330 --> 00:31:28.210
about the folkloric ballet, it
just made sense to me to do it

00:31:28.210 --> 00:31:31.850
about Amalia Hernandez, a woman
that really dedicated her life

00:31:31.850 --> 00:31:36.250
to learning about the
traditional dances of Mexico

00:31:36.250 --> 00:31:40.220
and to then being able to
adapt them to the theater

00:31:40.220 --> 00:31:45.530
and being able to share
then in the world stage.

00:31:45.530 --> 00:31:50.740
So, again, I just want to say
thank you, I'm very grateful.

00:31:50.740 --> 00:31:52.040
I'm very happy.

00:31:52.040 --> 00:31:56.960
I feel very fortunate for
all the support and for all

00:31:56.960 --> 00:31:58.300
that the Americas Award does.

00:31:58.300 --> 00:32:00.510
So thank you very much.

00:32:00.510 --> 00:32:20.040
[ Applause ]

00:32:20.040 --> 00:32:22.880
&gt;&gt; Paula Mason: Carefully.

00:32:22.880 --> 00:32:24.180
[laughter] Good afternoon.

00:32:24.180 --> 00:32:26.910
My name is Paula Mason, and
I'm a reference librarian

00:32:26.910 --> 00:32:30.080
at the Waukesha Public
Library in Wisconsin.

00:32:30.080 --> 00:32:32.440
It's a great honor to
be here with you today.

00:32:32.440 --> 00:32:33.910
I have the privilege

00:32:33.910 --> 00:32:37.580
of introducing a truly
phenomenal author, Ibi Zoboi,

00:32:37.580 --> 00:32:41.130
whose debut fiction title
American Streets moved our

00:32:41.130 --> 00:32:44.040
hearts and spirit
immensely this year.

00:32:44.040 --> 00:32:46.990
Through Ibi's confident
and powerful prose,

00:32:46.990 --> 00:32:48.940
we have the chance
to meet Fabiola,

00:32:48.940 --> 00:32:50.830
a young Haitian teenager

00:32:50.830 --> 00:32:53.710
who finds herself painfully
separated from her mother

00:32:53.710 --> 00:32:57.040
as they seek une belle
vie, a beautiful future,

00:32:57.040 --> 00:33:01.220
in the United States with her
aunt and cousins in Detroit.

00:33:01.220 --> 00:33:05.210
This story is so many things as
once, but to name just a few,

00:33:05.210 --> 00:33:10.060
it's a tale of great bravery,
resilience of spirit and faith,

00:33:10.060 --> 00:33:13.440
and a culture and a family which
helped carry us through times

00:33:13.440 --> 00:33:16.780
of unimaginable loss and
rebuilding our future

00:33:16.780 --> 00:33:19.160
when everything falls apart.

00:33:19.160 --> 00:33:21.730
It also pierces through
our hearts and minds

00:33:21.730 --> 00:33:25.140
with the timeliest of
themes, such as immigration,

00:33:25.140 --> 00:33:27.660
family separation, and
the senseless tragedy

00:33:27.660 --> 00:33:30.220
of the young lives lost.

00:33:30.220 --> 00:33:33.640
However, at the crossroads
of American Street,

00:33:33.640 --> 00:33:37.070
Ibi never leaves the
reader behind without hope.

00:33:37.070 --> 00:33:39.780
Rather, she brings
us alongside Fabiola

00:33:39.780 --> 00:33:42.340
and her ever-evolving
journey towards achieving her

00:33:42.340 --> 00:33:43.670
own dreams.

00:33:43.670 --> 00:33:46.690
Thank you so much for this
gift, Ibi, and it is an honor

00:33:46.690 --> 00:33:49.220
to present you, to have
you here and present you

00:33:49.220 --> 00:33:52.510
with an Americas Award.

00:33:52.510 --> 00:34:09.210
[ Applause ]

00:34:09.210 --> 00:34:11.250
&gt;&gt; Ibi Zoboi: Good
afternoon everyone.

00:34:11.250 --> 00:34:13.190
Thank you so much.

00:34:13.190 --> 00:34:16.380
This is such a huge
honor for me.

00:34:16.380 --> 00:34:22.330
Thank you to the consortium for
Latin American Studies programs

00:34:22.330 --> 00:34:26.640
and everyone involved in this
award and award ceremony.

00:34:26.640 --> 00:34:28.520
I'd like to thank my publisher,

00:34:28.520 --> 00:34:32.230
Harper Collins [inaudible]
imprint, and I'd also

00:34:32.230 --> 00:34:34.860
like to thank my editors,
Alisandra Balzer [phonetic]

00:34:34.860 --> 00:34:37.750
and Haley Lagwich [phonetic] of
Alloy [phonetic] Entertainment.

00:34:37.750 --> 00:34:40.780
I'd like to thank my
family and all the programs,

00:34:40.780 --> 00:34:44.380
the writing programs and the
workshops that got me here.

00:34:44.380 --> 00:34:48.560
I've been writing for 15 years
and trying to get published.

00:34:48.560 --> 00:34:53.000
American Street is my debut
novel, and I'm so happy

00:34:53.000 --> 00:34:57.400
and thrilled and honored to
see how it's been honored

00:34:57.400 --> 00:35:01.060
over the last two years,
the feedback from teachers,

00:35:01.060 --> 00:35:05.530
librarians, and students, and
I'm just overjoyed at the fact

00:35:05.530 --> 00:35:09.180
that readers, young readers, are
still discovering this story.

00:35:09.180 --> 00:35:13.260
I will share a little bit about
why, how American Street came

00:35:13.260 --> 00:35:17.520
to be, why this sort of story
is very important to me,

00:35:17.520 --> 00:35:22.100
and most importantly, I'm really
grateful that I am honored

00:35:22.100 --> 00:35:28.350
by an award that upholds
Latin American culture.

00:35:28.350 --> 00:35:31.420
I am a Haitian immigrant,
and as you know,

00:35:31.420 --> 00:35:33.990
Haiti is not a Spanish-speaking
country.

00:35:33.990 --> 00:35:39.350
It is a Francophone Caribbean
nation, and based on that fact,

00:35:39.350 --> 00:35:41.970
it kind of stands
out on it's own.

00:35:41.970 --> 00:35:45.290
However, it is also a
Latin American country

00:35:45.290 --> 00:35:49.610
which I just discovered I never
considered Haiti being part

00:35:49.610 --> 00:35:54.710
of this larger conversation
of Spanish-speaking countries

00:35:54.710 --> 00:35:58.190
or ever associating
it to anything Latin.

00:35:58.190 --> 00:36:00.750
Our history was that
of revolution,

00:36:00.750 --> 00:36:05.570
of French colonization and
African cultural retentions.

00:36:05.570 --> 00:36:09.460
So only recently did I begin
to think about what it means

00:36:09.460 --> 00:36:13.730
to be a Latin American
nation and what it means

00:36:13.730 --> 00:36:17.270
to be an Afro-Latinx nation.

00:36:17.270 --> 00:36:21.430
My recently published book is
called Pride, it's the Pride

00:36:21.430 --> 00:36:24.230
and Prejudice remix, or
just a light retelling

00:36:24.230 --> 00:36:25.530
of the literary classic,

00:36:25.530 --> 00:36:28.860
and it features a
Haitian-Dominican character.

00:36:28.860 --> 00:36:31.450
And as you may or may not know,

00:36:31.450 --> 00:36:35.690
Haiti and Dominican
Republic have been at odds,

00:36:35.690 --> 00:36:39.710
historical odds, cultural
odds, and you know,

00:36:39.710 --> 00:36:42.820
there's a language
barrier as well.

00:36:42.820 --> 00:36:46.770
And I was thrilled
that Elizabeth Acevedo,

00:36:46.770 --> 00:36:50.040
who is a Dominican author,
the author of Poet X,

00:36:50.040 --> 00:36:52.000
did the narration for Pride.

00:36:52.000 --> 00:36:54.470
And in that process,
in that sort

00:36:54.470 --> 00:36:57.760
of collaboration we realized
that we were healing both

00:36:57.760 --> 00:37:00.090
of our respective countries.

00:37:00.090 --> 00:37:05.540
So being honored for this
award that has the title Latin

00:37:05.540 --> 00:37:09.970
in it is also just, it means
a lot to me, because Haiti

00:37:09.970 --> 00:37:13.470
in itself can be very isolated

00:37:13.470 --> 00:37:16.230
from the larger Caribbean
culture

00:37:16.230 --> 00:37:19.200
and within the western
hemisphere itself,

00:37:19.200 --> 00:37:23.270
being dubbed the poorest country
in the western hemisphere,

00:37:23.270 --> 00:37:26.790
being one of the countries
that has the closest ties

00:37:26.790 --> 00:37:33.460
to African culture, and part
of writing American Street was

00:37:33.460 --> 00:37:38.210
about retaining the
culture that has been sort

00:37:38.210 --> 00:37:41.260
of bastardized in
the western media.

00:37:41.260 --> 00:37:45.300
In American Street, Fabiola
holds onto her Vaudou culture,

00:37:45.300 --> 00:37:49.720
and it meant a lot to me to
make that authentic and real

00:37:49.720 --> 00:37:52.100
and not make our traditions

00:37:52.100 --> 00:37:56.810
and our culture a
caricature in this novel.

00:37:56.810 --> 00:38:01.960
And when readers and
thought leaders, teachers,

00:38:01.960 --> 00:38:07.930
and librarians recognize that,
to me that is sort of defiance

00:38:07.930 --> 00:38:13.390
and a pushback against what the
mainstream has been feeding us

00:38:13.390 --> 00:38:16.930
for the last few decades
about my home country.

00:38:16.930 --> 00:38:20.330
So, I'm going to share
the author's note

00:38:20.330 --> 00:38:24.010
from American Street,
because I've only written it.

00:38:24.010 --> 00:38:28.930
I remember it being a tough
process between my editors and I

00:38:28.930 --> 00:38:33.740
to figure out the how's and
why of this story so that

00:38:33.740 --> 00:38:36.600
when readers turn to the
last page, whatever it is

00:38:36.600 --> 00:38:39.700
that happens in that last
scene in American Street,

00:38:39.700 --> 00:38:43.190
there's an author's
note for readers to kind

00:38:43.190 --> 00:38:47.090
of unpack what has
happened and for readers

00:38:47.090 --> 00:38:49.740
to understand my intentions.

00:38:49.740 --> 00:38:54.070
One of the things that really
care about is being understood.

00:38:54.070 --> 00:38:57.410
And I don't always have,
authors don't always have the

00:38:57.410 --> 00:39:00.650
opportunity to state their
intentions in a book,

00:39:00.650 --> 00:39:04.380
and sometimes we have a certain
sort of insecurity in terms

00:39:04.380 --> 00:39:07.780
of did I get my meaning
across, did I get,

00:39:07.780 --> 00:39:10.970
did readers understand
what I was trying to do,

00:39:10.970 --> 00:39:15.970
and sometimes those validations
come from awards like this.

00:39:15.970 --> 00:39:20.070
And it also comes from the
committees who plan those awards

00:39:20.070 --> 00:39:23.760
and read other books and put
your work up against others

00:39:23.760 --> 00:39:26.830
and others that are
really qualified

00:39:26.830 --> 00:39:30.410
as well and see it's value.

00:39:30.410 --> 00:39:32.490
So, again, I have
to say thank you.

00:39:32.490 --> 00:39:34.790
I have to put this down.

00:39:39.040 --> 00:39:41.130
So while I did not
come to this country

00:39:41.130 --> 00:39:43.480
as a 16-year-old, Fabiola did.

00:39:43.480 --> 00:39:47.080
I came to this country
as a four-year-old.

00:39:47.080 --> 00:39:49.200
I moved, the first
neighborhood I moved

00:39:49.200 --> 00:39:53.240
to in New York is a neighborhood
called Bushwick, Brooklyn,

00:39:53.240 --> 00:39:57.380
and I'll explain a little
bit more about Bushwick

00:39:57.380 --> 00:40:00.780
and what it means to come
from such a beautiful island,

00:40:00.780 --> 00:40:05.370
I think all the Latin Americas
are like that, tropical, warm,

00:40:05.370 --> 00:40:11.340
family, love, food, and to have
that American dream and to come

00:40:11.340 --> 00:40:15.110
from what's considered a broken
nation by the western media,

00:40:15.110 --> 00:40:18.640
and it is in many
ways, to a broken city,

00:40:18.640 --> 00:40:21.280
which Detroit is still
coming back from,

00:40:21.280 --> 00:40:24.380
and many of our cities are
like this as well, and the kind

00:40:24.380 --> 00:40:29.260
of conflict that happens
in that sort of exchange.

00:40:29.260 --> 00:40:32.210
So the first seeds of American
Street were planted in me

00:40:32.210 --> 00:40:36.520
when I read a New York Times
article entitled Last Stop

00:40:36.520 --> 00:40:39.750
on the L Train, Detroit.

00:40:39.750 --> 00:40:42.390
The article was about the
far-reaching gentrification

00:40:42.390 --> 00:40:45.160
of Brooklyn, New York, and it's
progression towards Detroit,

00:40:45.160 --> 00:40:46.640
Michigan.

00:40:46.640 --> 00:40:49.370
The real last stop on
the L train is Canarsie,

00:40:49.370 --> 00:40:51.860
but Bushwick is the
last stop for whites

00:40:51.860 --> 00:40:56.630
and affluent residents who won't
venture too deep into Brooklyn.

00:40:56.630 --> 00:40:59.390
I was four years old when
my mother and I left Haiti,

00:40:59.390 --> 00:41:01.240
and Bushwick was our
first home in America.

00:41:01.240 --> 00:41:06.650
I didn't know it then, but
1980s Bushwick was described

00:41:06.650 --> 00:41:09.430
as resembling a war zone.

00:41:09.430 --> 00:41:14.030
While our house on Hancock
Street was fairly intact,

00:41:14.030 --> 00:41:16.440
other blocks were lined
with burnt-out buildings

00:41:16.440 --> 00:41:21.040
and open lots littered with
torn mattresses and old tires.

00:41:21.040 --> 00:41:24.190
When I read the New York Times
article, I remember thinking,

00:41:24.190 --> 00:41:26.040
how does present-day
Detroit compare

00:41:26.040 --> 00:41:27.610
to the Bushwick I grew up in?

00:41:27.610 --> 00:41:31.470
It seems like there were too
many parallels to ignore.

00:41:31.470 --> 00:41:33.980
I could transpose my
own life as an immigrant

00:41:33.980 --> 00:41:36.110
onto the timelines of Detroit.

00:41:36.110 --> 00:41:38.600
I could write a book that
rides the train from Bushwick

00:41:38.600 --> 00:41:41.840
to Detroit and tell the
story of a girl, like me,

00:41:41.840 --> 00:41:45.400
who found her way
to the other side.

00:41:45.400 --> 00:41:48.690
While writing American Street,
I pulled from my own memories

00:41:48.690 --> 00:41:52.600
of living in between
cultures, the experiences I had

00:41:52.600 --> 00:41:54.590
in high school and the
many tragic stories

00:41:54.590 --> 00:41:58.660
about the violence and trauma
that girls have endured.

00:41:58.660 --> 00:42:01.020
In Haiti, many girls
dream of freedom to live

00:42:01.020 --> 00:42:03.770
without the constraints
of oppression.

00:42:03.770 --> 00:42:06.250
Yet, more often than
not, these girls

00:42:06.250 --> 00:42:09.440
and their families leave their
home countries only to move

00:42:09.440 --> 00:42:12.760
to other broken and
disenfranchised communities.

00:42:12.760 --> 00:42:16.290
I kept thinking about how these
girls negotiate their own values

00:42:16.290 --> 00:42:19.630
and culture with the
need to survive and aim

00:42:19.630 --> 00:42:20.930
for the American dream.

00:42:20.930 --> 00:42:26.700
When Trayvon Martin was killed
in Florida in February of 2012,

00:42:26.700 --> 00:42:30.710
he had been on the phone with
Rachel Jeantel, the daughter

00:42:30.710 --> 00:42:32.760
of a Haitian immigrant.

00:42:32.760 --> 00:42:35.620
During her testimony in
the George Zimmerman trial,

00:42:35.620 --> 00:42:39.500
I recognized a little
bit of myself in Rachel

00:42:39.500 --> 00:42:41.930
and in the many Haitian
teen girls I've worked

00:42:41.930 --> 00:42:43.750
with over the years.

00:42:43.750 --> 00:42:46.760
We fold our immigrant
selves into this veneer

00:42:46.760 --> 00:42:50.120
of what we think is
African American girlhood.

00:42:50.120 --> 00:42:52.930
The result is more
jagged than smooth.

00:42:52.930 --> 00:42:55.780
This tension between
our inherited identity

00:42:55.780 --> 00:43:00.360
and our newly adopted selves
filters into our relationships

00:43:00.360 --> 00:43:03.610
with other girls, with the boys
we love, and how we interact

00:43:03.610 --> 00:43:06.940
with the broken [inaudible]
around us.

00:43:06.940 --> 00:43:08.590
I saw Fabiola in these girls,

00:43:08.590 --> 00:43:11.860
and that's how the
story was truly born.

00:43:11.860 --> 00:43:15.090
I wanted to give Fabiola a
strong cultural connection

00:43:15.090 --> 00:43:18.450
to Haiti so that she's
spiritually grounded when faced

00:43:18.450 --> 00:43:20.410
with a tough decision.

00:43:20.410 --> 00:43:23.540
While Vaudou is practiced by
many in the Haitian diaspora,

00:43:23.540 --> 00:43:26.240
it still has a negative
stereotype in the media

00:43:26.240 --> 00:43:30.330
as being associated with
evil and witchcraft.

00:43:30.330 --> 00:43:35.240
Vaudou has a complex pantheon
and mythological system much

00:43:35.240 --> 00:43:36.970
like Greek and Roman mythology.

00:43:36.970 --> 00:43:41.150
Through Fabiola's eyes, her
new world and the people

00:43:41.150 --> 00:43:45.030
who inhabit it are just
as complex and magical

00:43:45.030 --> 00:43:46.870
as her beloved saint
[inaudible].

00:43:46.870 --> 00:43:50.730
She infused Vaudou into
everything that happens to her.

00:43:50.730 --> 00:43:53.020
This is the source of courage,

00:43:53.020 --> 00:43:56.290
and I think she is more
American because of it.

00:43:56.290 --> 00:44:00.150
This merging of traditions,
this blending of cultures

00:44:00.150 --> 00:44:03.450
from one broken place
to another.

00:44:03.450 --> 00:44:08.010
I remember those rides on the L
train with my mother very well.

00:44:08.010 --> 00:44:11.490
Graffiti covered every
inch of the train cars.

00:44:11.490 --> 00:44:14.550
I once saw a young man steel
a diamond ring right off a

00:44:14.550 --> 00:44:16.300
woman's finger.

00:44:16.300 --> 00:44:19.720
My mother pulled me in close
and prayed under her breath.

00:44:19.720 --> 00:44:23.790
We'd made it to the other
side, just like Fabiola,

00:44:23.790 --> 00:44:27.070
but what was this life?

00:44:27.070 --> 00:44:29.440
I don't know what my life would
have been like if I had grown

00:44:29.440 --> 00:44:33.100
up in Haiti, but I
know this much is true.

00:44:33.100 --> 00:44:36.450
I would not have
told this story.

00:44:36.450 --> 00:44:38.510
Thank you very much.

00:44:38.510 --> 00:44:51.040
[ Applause ]

00:44:51.040 --> 00:44:52.340
&gt;&gt; Colleen McCoy:
Thank you, Ibi.

00:44:52.340 --> 00:44:53.640
Hi everyone.

00:44:53.640 --> 00:44:55.400
My name is Colleen McCoy,
and I am the co-coordinator

00:44:55.400 --> 00:44:57.100
of the Americas Award.

00:44:57.100 --> 00:45:00.980
Thank you, again, to the Library
of Congress, to Georgette Dorn,

00:45:00.980 --> 00:45:04.570
Catalina Gomez, and the Hispanic
division, to the founder

00:45:04.570 --> 00:45:06.970
of the Americas Award,
Julie Kline,

00:45:06.970 --> 00:45:10.180
and to all of the authors,
illustrators, and publishers

00:45:10.180 --> 00:45:13.210
